\r\n\r\n<str> Content </str>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 22:59:50','2014-08-13 22:59:50','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=28',0,'revision','',0),(29,1,'2014-08-13 23:01:51','2014-08-13 23:01:51','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of information that would have been helpful to us was a simple overview of what each option in Drupal\'s administration menu does. Since we were unable to find such a resource, we decided to create one ourselves.\r\n\r\n<str> Getting Started </str>\r\nThe drupal login page can be found at yoursitename.com/user.\r\nWhen you’re logged in as an administrator, you should see a black bar across the top with the options Dashboard, Content, Structure, Appearance, People, Modules, Configuration, Reports, and Help.\r\nHere’s the default Drupal home page, using the Bartik theme, as it looks when an administrator is logged in. Your site name will probably be different.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"488\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-26\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<str> Dashboard </str>\r\nThe dashboard is not particularly important for configuring the site overall. It allows you to see some recently posted content as well as users of the site. It’s a little bit like a facebook news feed for your Drupal site, which essentially makes it useless.\r\n\r\n<str> Content </str>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>\r\nThis is where you can add and delete content, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<str> Stucture </str>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<str>Blocks</str>\r\n\r\n<li>','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 23:01:51','2014-08-13 23:01:51','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=29',0,'revision','',0),(30,1,'2014-08-13 23:02:35','2014-08-13 23:02:35','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of information that would have been helpful to us was a simple overview of what each option in Drupal\'s administration menu does. Since we were unable to find such a resource, we decided to create one ourselves.\r\n\r\n<b> Getting Started </b>\r\nThe drupal login page can be found at yoursitename.com/user.\r\nWhen you’re logged in as an administrator, you should see a black bar across the top with the options Dashboard, Content, Structure, Appearance, People, Modules, Configuration, Reports, and Help.\r\nHere’s the default Drupal home page, using the Bartik theme, as it looks when an administrator is logged in. Your site name will probably be different.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"488\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-26\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Dashboard </b>\r\nThe dashboard is not particularly important for configuring the site overall. It allows you to see some recently posted content as well as users of the site. It’s a little bit like a facebook news feed for your Drupal site, which essentially makes it useless.\r\n\r\n<b> Content </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>\r\nThis is where you can add and delete content, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<b> Stucture </b>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<str>Blocks</str>\r\n\r\n<li>','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 23:02:35','2014-08-13 23:02:35','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=30',0,'revision','',0),(31,1,'2014-08-13 23:04:59','2014-08-13 23:04:59','','3','','inherit','open','open','','3','','','2014-08-13 23:04:59','2014-08-13 23:04:59','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(32,1,'2014-08-13 23:07:24','2014-08-13 23:07:24','','4','','inherit','open','open','','4','','','2014-08-13 23:07:24','2014-08-13 23:07:24','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(33,1,'2014-08-13 23:07:32','2014-08-13 23:07:32','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of information that would have been helpful to us was a simple overview of what each option in Drupal\'s administration menu does. Since we were unable to find such a resource, we decided to create one ourselves.\r\n\r\n<b> Getting Started </b>\r\nThe drupal login page can be found at yoursitename.com/user.\r\nWhen you’re logged in as an administrator, you should see a black bar across the top with the options Dashboard, Content, Structure, Appearance, People, Modules, Configuration, Reports, and Help.\r\nHere’s the default Drupal home page, using the Bartik theme, as it looks when an administrator is logged in. Your site name will probably be different.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"488\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-26\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Dashboard </b>\r\nThe dashboard is not particularly important for configuring the site overall. It allows you to see some recently posted content as well as users of the site. It’s a little bit like a facebook news feed for your Drupal site, which essentially makes it useless.\r\n\r\n<b> Content </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>\r\nThis is where you can add and delete content, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<b> Stucture </b>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\" alt=\"3\" width=\"780\" height=\"457\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-31\" /></a>\r\nUnder blocks, you will find a page that lists the regions and blocks of your site. Regions are listed in bold, and are where you can assign blocks. Blocks are not in bold, and you should see a four way arrow to the left of each block title, a drop-down to the right of the title allowing you to select a region, and a “configure” link.\r\n\r\n<b>What Are Regions and Blocks?</b>\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\nBlocks are things such as content, menus, menu items, search bars, forms, widgets, and user logins. Blocks are typically the outputs of modules. Modules provide different functionalities to Drupal. We’ll talk more about modules later.\r\n\r\n<b>Regions</b>\r\nRegions are different areas of your site. If you click on Demonstrate Block Regions (just under the description on the opening Blocks page), you should see different areas of your site highlighted in yellow. These are regions, and they are essentially just different places you can put blocks. Regions are defined by the theme of your Drupal site, and so will vary depending on which theme you have installed and set to default. We’ll talk more about themes later. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\" alt=\"4\" width=\"314\" height=\"196\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32\" /></a>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 23:07:32','2014-08-13 23:07:32','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=33',0,'revision','',0),(34,1,'2014-08-13 23:08:57','2014-08-13 23:08:57','','5','','inherit','open','open','','5','','','2014-08-13 23:08:57','2014-08-13 23:08:57','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/201