he one on the Blocks page. You can choose to add images, taxonomy, and other options as fields. Modules that you install may provide additional field types to use in your content type. You can drag the fields into different positions using the four way arrows.\r\n\r\n<b>The Manage Display Tab</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\" alt=\"10\" width=\"522\" height=\"281\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-44\" /></a>\r\nUnder manage display, you can change the way the content type is displayed when it is in a feed such as the one that appears by default on the home page.\r\n\r\n<b>Comment Fields and Comment Display</b> \r\nIf you intend to allow commenting on your site, this is where you would configure it.\r\n\r\n<b>Adding a Content Type</b>\r\nWhen you add a content type, it is very similar to editing an already existent content type. You will have to go through a series of screens, similar to the tabs, that let you fill in the options for the content types.\r\n\r\n\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-13 23:34:31','2014-08-13 23:34:31','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=47',0,'revision','',0),(48,1,'2014-08-13 23:36:10','2014-08-13 23:36:10','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of 