nt, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<b> Stucture </b>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\" alt=\"3\" width=\"780\" height=\"457\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-31\" /></a>\r\nUnder blocks, you will find a page that lists the regions and blocks of your site. Regions are listed in bold, and are where you can assign blocks. Blocks are not in bold, and you should see a four way arrow to the left of each block title, a drop-down to the right of the title allowing you to select a region, and a “configure” link.\r\n\r\n<b>What Are Regions and Blocks?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\nBlocks are things such as content, menus, menu items, search bars, forms, widgets, and user logins. Blocks are typically the outputs of modules. Modules provide different functionalities to Drupal. We’ll talk more about modules later.\r\n\r\n<b>Regions</b>\r\nRegions are different areas of your site. If you click on Demonstrate Block Regions (just under the description on the opening Blocks page), you should see different areas of your site highlighted in yellow. These are regions, and they are essentially just different places you can put blocks. Regions are defined by the theme of your Drupal site, and so will vary depending on which theme you have installed and set to default. We’ll talk more about themes later. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\" alt=\"4\" width=\"314\" height=\"196\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Adding and Configuring Blocks </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\" alt=\"5\" width=\"780\" height=\"440\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-34\" /></a>\r\nTo add a block, you can click the + Add Block at the top of the page. The Add Block option allows you to enter plain text or full html, but doesn’t let you create more complicated blocks. That’s what modules are for. If you’ve enabled and properly configured a module (we’ll talk about how to do this later), if you scroll down the main Blocks page, you should be able to see blocks listed that the module has output. If you add a custom block, you should be taken back to the main blocks page.\r\n\r\nTo make a block appear on your home page, you need to place the block in a region. There are two ways to do this through the Blocks page. You can either drag the block to a region using the four way arrow, or you can select the region you wish to place it in using the drop-down menu to the right of the block’s name.\r\n\r\nTo configure a block, click on the “configure” link to the far right of the block’s name on the Blocks page. On the configure page, you can specify in what regions the block is displayed. Under visibility settings, you can choose which pages the block is displayed on, and which content types the block will be displayed for. You can also specify which Roles (Types of users) and which Users can see the block.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Types</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\" alt=\"6\" width=\"656\" height=\"297\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" /></a>\r\nHere, you can create new types of content and edit already existing content types. By default, Drupal includes the content types Article and Basic Page. Articles are typically used for more blog-like content, whereas Basic Pages are usually used for static content.\r\n\r\n<b>Editing An Already Existing Content Type</b>\r\nTo edit an already existing content type, click edit, manage fields, or manage display. Once you click on edit, manage fields, or manage display, the other links will show up as tabs when you’re editing the content type. Here, we’re on the edit tab and can see Manage Fields, Manage Display, Comment Fields, and Comment Display as other options.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\" alt=\"8\" width=\"780\" height=\"455\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-39\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>The Edit Tab</b>\r\nHere, we can set the name of the content type. We can also set submission form settings, which have to do with how content of that type will be created by a user. Publishing options let you choose whether or not the content will show up on your front page by default. \r\n\r\n<b>Manage Fields Tab</b><a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\" alt=\"9\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-42\" /></a>\r\nThis is an important part of editing a content type. Here, you get to choose what fields make up the content type. The interface here is similar to the one on the Blocks page. You can choose to add images, taxonomy, and other options as fields. Modules that you install may provide additional field types to use in your content type. You can drag the fields into different positions using the four way arrows.\r\n\r\n<b>The Manage Display Tab</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\" alt=\"10\" width=\"522\" height=\"281\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-44\" /></a>\r\nUnder manage display, you can change the way the content type is displayed when it is in a feed such as the one that appears by default on the home page.\r\n\r\n<b>Comment Fields and Comment Display</b> \r\nIf you intend to allow commenting on your site, this is where you would configure it.\r\n\r\n<b>Adding a Content Type</b>\r\nWhen you add a content type, it is very similar to editing an already existent content type. You will have to go through a series of screens, similar to the tabs, that let you fill in the options for the content types.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Menus</b>\r\nUnder menus, you can create or edit your site’s menus. These menus are a type of block and so can be placed using the Blocks page. The operations available for these menus are to list links, edit menu, and add link. Under list links, you can add, edit, and delete links from your menu. Under edit menu, you can change the name or description of your menu.\r\n </li>\r\n<li><b>Taxonomy</b>\r\nTaxonomy is a method that Drupal provides to organize content. Drupal taxonomies are made up of vocabularies. Vocabularies can be added as a field to a content type. The default vocabulary is tags, which work as one would expect. For example, you could add tags to an article just as you might add tags to a twitter post or tumblr post. \r\n\r\nYou can reorder taxonomy terms and create sub-vocabularies by dragging the taxonomy terms into different positions using the four way arrow.\r\n\r\nThere are several options given for operations allowed on vocabularies. Edit vocabularies gives you options for changing the name and description of the vocabularies. List terms lists all of the terms currently in a vocabulary and gives you options to edit or delete them.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Appearance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\" alt=\"11\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-49\" /></a>\r\nThe Appearance section is where you can set the theme for your site. All installed themes will be listed, with “Settings”, “Disable”, and “Set Default” options. Whichever theme is set as Default will be the one Drupal uses to display the pages on the site. The “Update” tab will show you when themes need to be updated, and the “Settings” tab will change settings for ALL themes on your site.\r\n\r\n<b>People </b> (Permissions are under this menu option. If something isn\'t displaying this may be why!)\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\" alt=\"12\" width=\"780\" height=\"407\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-51\" /></a>\r\nThis section has two subsections: “List” and “Permissions”. The “List” tab contains a list of all current registered users of the site with options to edit or remove accounts. \r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\" alt=\"13\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-53\" /></a>\r\nThe “Permissions” tab is more important, as it sets the permissions for various users to use different parts of the site. You will want to check this page periodically to ensure that Anonymous and/or Authenticated users are able to access functionality that may be default set to Administrator-only. In the “Permissions” tab, you can also configure Roles if you want to set more specific roles than the three provided.\r\n\r\n<b>Modules</b>\r\nModules\r\nWARNING:\r\nSome modules will completely break your website, so be cautious. Make sure that the module you’re installing has been updated fairly recently (within the last two years), that it is under active development, and that at least 1000 sites use the module. You’ll also want to make sure that the module is for Drupal 7.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\" alt=\"14\" width=\"780\" height=\"430\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-54\" /></a>\r\nThe modules section has three subsections: “List”, “Update”, and “Uninstall”. The “List” tab contains a list of all modules installed. In order to enable a module, you have to check the box next to its name, as well as enabling all the other modules it might depend on. Certain modules will also have “Permissions” and “Configure” options. It’s a good idea to check these for each module you install, and many modules will specifically guide you through their configurations. Some modules won’t do anything if you don’t correctly configure them.\r\n\r\nTo install new modules, you have two options. The first is to install the module through the GUI by clicking “Install new module”. Through this option, you can either install the module through a downloaded file from the Drupal website or by using a link to the file download. Once installed, the GUI will bring you to a page that will invite you to install new modules or to enable recently installed modules. The second is to manually install the files you’ve downloaded. To do this, you must have access to the /sites/all/modules folder of your domain. Unzip the module file in this folder, and then you will be able to enable the newly installed module through the GUI. \r\n\r\nIf you accidentally install a module that breaks everything on your site, often deleting the module from the /sites/all/modules folder will allow your site to load again.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\" alt=\"15\" width=\"780\" height=\"427\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>\r\nThe “Update” tab will tell you if any modules need updating. The “Uninstall” tab will list any modules that you have installed but disabled. If you want to uninstall any module you’ve installed, you simply have to disable it and any other modules that depend on it, and then it will appear in the “Uninstall” tab. You can uninstall it from there.\r\n\r\n<b>Configuration</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\" alt=\"16\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>\r\nThe Configuration page has many subsections for configuring various parts of the site.\r\n<ul> \r\n<li><b>People</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Account Settings</b>\r\nAccount Settings allows you to administer the settings for users signing up to your site. You can also configure the way user’s data is stored and how the profiles are displayed.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>IP Address Blocking </b>\r\nThis option allows you to block certain IP addresses, i.e., spam accounts, from accessing your site\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Authoring</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Text formats</b>\r\nThe three default text formats are sufficient for most uses, but if you need to configure the way the text of your content is read by Drupal, you can customize it here.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Media</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>File System</b>\r\nThis tells Drupal where to look for particular files. Unless you’re moving important files around, you shouldn’t need to modify this.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Styles</b>\r\nAgain, the default settings are fine for most uses here, but if you’d like to change the way particular images are displayed through the GUI, here’s where to go.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Toolkit</b>\r\nThe image toolkit allows you to adjust the default quality of images on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Search and Metadata</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Search Settings</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\" alt=\"17\" width=\"780\" height=\"422\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-62\" /></a>\r\nIn order for default search to work, it needs to be able to index your site. You can manually re-index here. You can also set the minimum number of characters to be indexed for search, whether you can search Nodes or Users, rank some content higher than others, and many more settings here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>URL Aliases</b>\r\nThis allows you to manually change certain URLs. If you will be changing many URLs, it makes sense to allow a module to do this instead. (See URL document).\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Clean URLs</b>\r\nIf you have clean URLs enabled, you will be able to remove unnecessary characters from URLs so that they simply look nicer. This does NOT necessarily make them good URLs for Search Engine Optimization, but it is a good first step.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Regional and Language</b>\r\n<ul> <li><b>Regional Settings</b>\r\nHere you may configure regional settings for default displays for time, date, etc.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Date and Time</b>\r\nAs above, this allows you to configure specifically how date and time are displayed on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>System</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Site Information</b>\r\nThis page allows you to configure various default site options such as number of posts displayed on the homepage and the URLs to the homepage and various 403/404 error pages.</li>\r\n<li><b>Actions</b>\r\nThe actions is another page that you probably won’t need to touch, but if you need to configure a specific action for a specific event on your site, go here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Cron</b>\r\nHere you can run cron manually or configure how often it is run. Cron is run when checking for updates or for reindexing your site; basically it is run anytime you need to update something on your site. It is usually enough to run Cron automatically, unless you want to manually check for specific updates (such as many new additions to your site).\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>User Interface</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Shorcuts</b>\r\nShortcuts allows you to set the shortcuts used on your Account page. This is different from the shortcuts you can set in the secondary Menu bar (the one that default reads “Add content” “Find content”). </li></ul>\r\n<li><b>Development</b> \r\n<ul><li><b>Performance</b>\r\nINSERT PERFORMANCE IMG HERE\r\n\r\n','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 00:03:52','2014-08-14 00:03:52','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=65',0,'revision','',0),(66,1,'2014-08-14 16:17:13','2014-08-14 16:17:13','','1','','inherit','open','open','','1-2','','','2014-08-14 16:17:13','2014-08-14 16:17:13','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(71,1,'2014-08-14 16:25:31','2014-08-14 16:25:31','','2','','inherit','open','open','','2-2','','','2014-08-14 16:25:31','2014-08-14 16:25:31','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/21.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(67,1,'2014-08-14 16:23:25','2014-08-14 16:23:25','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of information that would have been helpful to us was a simple overview of what each option in Drupal\'s administration menu does. Since we were unable to find such a resource, we decided to create one ourselves.\r\n\r\n<b> Getting Started </b>\r\nThe drupal login page can be found at yoursitename.com/user.\r\nWhen you’re logged in as an administrator, you should see a black bar across the top with the options Dashboard, Content, Structure, Appearance, People, Modules, Configuration, Reports, and Help.\r\nHere’s the default Drupal home page, using the Bartik theme, as it looks when an administrator is logged in. Your site name will probably be different.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"488\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-26\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Dashboard </b>\r\nThe dashboard is not particularly important for configuring the site overall. It allows you to see some recently posted content as well as users of the site. It’s a little bit like a facebook news feed for your Drupal site, which essentially makes it useless.\r\n\r\n<b> Content </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>\r\nThis is where you can add and delete content, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<b> Stucture </b>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\" alt=\"3\" width=\"780\" height=\"457\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-31\" /></a>\r\nUnder blocks, you will find a page that lists the regions and blocks of your site. Regions are listed in bold, and are where you can assign blocks. Blocks are not in bold, and you should see a four way arrow to the left of each block title, a drop-down to the right of the title allowing you to select a region, and a “configure” link.\r\n\r\n<b>What Are Regions and Blocks?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\nBlocks are things such as content, menus, menu items, search bars, forms, widgets, and user logins. Blocks are typically the outputs of modules. Modules provide different functionalities to Drupal. We’ll talk more about modules later.\r\n\r\n<b>Regions</b>\r\nRegions are different areas of your site. If you click on Demonstrate Block Regions (just under the description on the opening Blocks page), you should see different areas of your site highlighted in yellow. These are regions, and they are essentially just different places you can put blocks. Regions are defined by the theme of your Drupal site, and so will vary depending on which theme you have installed and set to default. We’ll talk more about themes later. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\" alt=\"4\" width=\"314\" height=\"196\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Adding and Configuring Blocks </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\" alt=\"5\" width=\"780\" height=\"440\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-34\" /></a>\r\nTo add a block, you can click the + Add Block at the top of the page. The Add Block option allows you to enter plain text or full html, but doesn’t let you create more complicated blocks. That’s what modules are for. If you’ve enabled and properly configured a module (we’ll talk about how to do this later), if you scroll down the main Blocks page, you should be able to see blocks listed that the module has output. If you add a custom block, you should be taken back to the main blocks page.\r\n\r\nTo make a block appear on your home page, you need to place the block in a region. There are two ways to do this through the Blocks page. You can either drag the block to a region using the four way arrow, or you can select the region you wish to place it in using the drop-down menu to the right of the block’s name.\r\n\r\nTo configure a block, click on the “configure” link to the far right of the block’s name on the Blocks page. On the configure page, you can specify in what regions the block is displayed. Under visibility settings, you can choose which pages the block is displayed on, and which content types the block will be displayed for. You can also specify which Roles (Types of users) and which Users can see the block.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Types</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\" alt=\"6\" width=\"656\" height=\"297\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" /></a>\r\nHere, you can create new types of content and edit already existing content types. By default, Drupal includes the content types Article and Basic Page. Articles are typically used for more blog-like content, whereas Basic Pages are usually used for static content.\r\n\r\n<b>Editing An Already Existing Content Type</b>\r\nTo edit an already existing content type, click edit, manage fields, or manage display. Once you click on edit, manage fields, or manage display, the other links will show up as tabs when you’re editing the content type. Here, we’re on the edit tab and can see Manage Fields, Manage Display, Comment Fields, and Comment Display as other options.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\" alt=\"8\" width=\"780\" height=\"455\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-39\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>The Edit Tab</b>\r\nHere, we can set the name of the content type. We can also set submission form settings, which have to do with how content of that type will be created by a user. Publishing options let you choose whether or not the content will show up on your front page by default. \r\n\r\n<b>Manage Fields Tab</b><a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\" alt=\"9\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-42\" /></a>\r\nThis is an important part of editing a content type. Here, you get to choose what fields make up the content type. The interface here is similar to the one on the Blocks page. You can choose to add images, taxonomy, and other options as fields. Modules that you install may provide additional field types to use in your content type. You can drag the fields into different positions using the four way arrows.\r\n\r\n<b>The Manage Display Tab</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\" alt=\"10\" width=\"522\" height=\"281\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-44\" /></a>\r\nUnder manage display, you can change the way the content type is displayed when it is in a feed such as the one that appears by default on the home page.\r\n\r\n<b>Comment Fields and Comment Display</b> \r\nIf you intend to allow commenting on your site, this is where you would configure it.\r\n\r\n<b>Adding a Content Type</b>\r\nWhen you add a content type, it is very similar to editing an already existent content type. You will have to go through a series of screens, similar to the tabs, that let you fill in the options for the content types.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Menus</b>\r\nUnder menus, you can create or edit your site’s menus. These menus are a type of block and so can be placed using the Blocks page. The operations available for these menus are to list links, edit menu, and add link. Under list links, you can add, edit, and delete links from your menu. Under edit menu, you can change the name or description of your menu.\r\n </li>\r\n<li><b>Taxonomy</b>\r\nTaxonomy is a method that Drupal provides to organize content. Drupal taxonomies are made up of vocabularies. Vocabularies can be added as a field to a content type. The default vocabulary is tags, which work as one would expect. For example, you could add tags to an article just as you might add tags to a twitter post or tumblr post. \r\n\r\nYou can reorder taxonomy terms and create sub-vocabularies by dragging the taxonomy terms into different positions using the four way arrow.\r\n\r\nThere are several options given for operations allowed on vocabularies. Edit vocabularies gives you options for changing the name and description of the vocabularies. List terms lists all of the terms currently in a vocabulary and gives you options to edit or delete them.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Appearance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\" alt=\"11\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-49\" /></a>\r\nThe Appearance section is where you can set the theme for your site. All installed themes will be listed, with “Settings”, “Disable”, and “Set Default” options. Whichever theme is set as Default will be the one Drupal uses to display the pages on the site. The “Update” tab will show you when themes need to be updated, and the “Settings” tab will change settings for ALL themes on your site.\r\n\r\n<b>People </b> (Permissions are under this menu option. If something isn\'t displaying this may be why!)\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\" alt=\"12\" width=\"780\" height=\"407\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-51\" /></a>\r\nThis section has two subsections: “List” and “Permissions”. The “List” tab contains a list of all current registered users of the site with options to edit or remove accounts. \r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\" alt=\"13\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-53\" /></a>\r\nThe “Permissions” tab is more important, as it sets the permissions for various users to use different parts of the site. You will want to check this page periodically to ensure that Anonymous and/or Authenticated users are able to access functionality that may be default set to Administrator-only. In the “Permissions” tab, you can also configure Roles if you want to set more specific roles than the three provided.\r\n\r\n<b>Modules</b>\r\nModules\r\nWARNING:\r\nSome modules will completely break your website, so be cautious. Make sure that the module you’re installing has been updated fairly recently (within the last two years), that it is under active development, and that at least 1000 sites use the module. You’ll also want to make sure that the module is for Drupal 7.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\" alt=\"14\" width=\"780\" height=\"430\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-54\" /></a>\r\nThe modules section has three subsections: “List”, “Update”, and “Uninstall”. The “List” tab contains a list of all modules installed. In order to enable a module, you have to check the box next to its name, as well as enabling all the other modules it might depend on. Certain modules will also have “Permissions” and “Configure” options. It’s a good idea to check these for each module you install, and many modules will specifically guide you through their configurations. Some modules won’t do anything if you don’t correctly configure them.\r\n\r\nTo install new modules, you have two options. The first is to install the module through the GUI by clicking “Install new module”. Through this option, you can either install the module through a downloaded file from the Drupal website or by using a link to the file download. Once installed, the GUI will bring you to a page that will invite you to install new modules or to enable recently installed modules. The second is to manually install the files you’ve downloaded. To do this, you must have access to the /sites/all/modules folder of your domain. Unzip the module file in this folder, and then you will be able to enable the newly installed module through the GUI. \r\n\r\nIf you accidentally install a module that breaks everything on your site, often deleting the module from the /sites/all/modules folder will allow your site to load again.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\" alt=\"15\" width=\"780\" height=\"427\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>\r\nThe “Update” tab will tell you if any modules need updating. The “Uninstall” tab will list any modules that you have installed but disabled. If you want to uninstall any module you’ve installed, you simply have to disable it and any other modules that depend on it, and then it will appear in the “Uninstall” tab. You can uninstall it from there.\r\n\r\n<b>Configuration</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\" alt=\"16\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>\r\nThe Configuration page has many subsections for configuring various parts of the site.\r\n<ul> \r\n<li><b>People</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Account Settings</b>\r\nAccount Settings allows you to administer the settings for users signing up to your site. You can also configure the way user’s data is stored and how the profiles are displayed.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>IP Address Blocking </b>\r\nThis option allows you to block certain IP addresses, i.e., spam accounts, from accessing your site\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Authoring</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Text formats</b>\r\nThe three default text formats are sufficient for most uses, but if you need to configure the way the text of your content is read by Drupal, you can customize it here.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Media</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>File System</b>\r\nThis tells Drupal where to look for particular files. Unless you’re moving important files around, you shouldn’t need to modify this.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Styles</b>\r\nAgain, the default settings are fine for most uses here, but if you’d like to change the way particular images are displayed through the GUI, here’s where to go.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Toolkit</b>\r\nThe image toolkit allows you to adjust the default quality of images on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Search and Metadata</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Search Settings</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\" alt=\"17\" width=\"780\" height=\"422\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-62\" /></a>\r\nIn order for default search to work, it needs to be able to index your site. You can manually re-index here. You can also set the minimum number of characters to be indexed for search, whether you can search Nodes or Users, rank some content higher than others, and many more settings here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>URL Aliases</b>\r\nThis allows you to manually change certain URLs. If you will be changing many URLs, it makes sense to allow a module to do this instead. (See URL document).\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Clean URLs</b>\r\nIf you have clean URLs enabled, you will be able to remove unnecessary characters from URLs so that they simply look nicer. This does NOT necessarily make them good URLs for Search Engine Optimization, but it is a good first step.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Regional and Language</b>\r\n<ul> <li><b>Regional Settings</b>\r\nHere you may configure regional settings for default displays for time, date, etc.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Date and Time</b>\r\nAs above, this allows you to configure specifically how date and time are displayed on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>System</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Site Information</b>\r\nThis page allows you to configure various default site options such as number of posts displayed on the homepage and the URLs to the homepage and various 403/404 error pages.</li>\r\n<li><b>Actions</b>\r\nThe actions is another page that you probably won’t need to touch, but if you need to configure a specific action for a specific event on your site, go here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Cron</b>\r\nHere you can run cron manually or configure how often it is run. Cron is run when checking for updates or for reindexing your site; basically it is run anytime you need to update something on your site. It is usually enough to run Cron automatically, unless you want to manually check for specific updates (such as many new additions to your site).\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>User Interface</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Shorcuts</b>\r\nShortcuts allows you to set the shortcuts used on your Account page. This is different from the shortcuts you can set in the secondary Menu bar (the one that default reads “Add content” “Find content”). </li></ul>\r\n<li><b>Development</b> \r\n<ul><li><b>Performance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"425\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-66\" /></a>\r\nThe performance page is most useful for clearing the cache (which you will have to do so often it is probably logical to make a shortcut for it on the aforementioned Menu bar. To do this, click on “Edit shortcuts”, then add a new shortcut with the url admin/config/development/performance. This will take you directly to the performance page and will save you a lot of clicks!). This page can also help with Search Engine Optimization, as it includes bandwidth optimization settings.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Logging and Errors</b>\r\nThis allows you to set the way that Drupal can show you error messages. The default settings are usually good except in special cases.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Maintenance Mode</b>\r\nYou will want to put your site into maintenance mode if you’re going to be installing major updates or making major changes to your live site. It will provide a maintenance message to users attempting to visit the site and stop all access to the site until you turn it off.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Web Services</b></li>\r\n<ul><li><b>RSS Publishing</b>\r\nThis allows you to configure default settings for how your content will appear in an RSS feed.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>As you install more modules to your site, there may be more module-specific options under the Configuration page, but not for all modules. You can always configure modules from the Modules tab.</li>\r\n\r\n','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 16:23:25','2014-08-14 16:23:25','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=67',0,'revision','',0),(69,1,'2014-08-14 16:24:28','2014-08-14 16:24:28','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of information that would have been helpful to us was a simple overview of what each option in Drupal\'s administration menu does. Since we were unable to find such a resource, we decided to create one ourselves.\r\n\r\n<b> Getting Started </b>\r\nThe drupal login page can be found at yoursitename.com/user.\r\nWhen you’re logged in as an administrator, you should see a black bar across the top with the options Dashboard, Content, Structure, Appearance, People, Modules, Configuration, Reports, and Help.\r\nHere’s the default Drupal home page, using the Bartik theme, as it looks when an administrator is logged in. Your site name will probably be different.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"488\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-26\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Dashboard </b>\r\nThe dashboard is not particularly important for configuring the site overall. It allows you to see some recently posted content as well as users of the site. It’s a little bit like a facebook news feed for your Drupal site, which essentially makes it useless.\r\n\r\n<b> Content </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>\r\nThis is where you can add and delete content, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<b> Stucture </b>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\" alt=\"3\" width=\"780\" height=\"457\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-31\" /></a>\r\nUnder blocks, you will find a page that lists the regions and blocks of your site. Regions are listed in bold, and are where you can assign blocks. Blocks are not in bold, and you should see a four way arrow to the left of each block title, a drop-down to the right of the title allowing you to select a region, and a “configure” link.\r\n\r\n<b>What Are Regions and Blocks?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\nBlocks are things such as content, menus, menu items, search bars, forms, widgets, and user logins. Blocks are typically the outputs of modules. Modules provide different functionalities to Drupal. We’ll talk more about modules later.\r\n\r\n<b>Regions</b>\r\nRegions are different areas of your site. If you click on Demonstrate Block Regions (just under the description on the opening Blocks page), you should see different areas of your site highlighted in yellow. These are regions, and they are essentially just different places you can put blocks. Regions are defined by the theme of your Drupal site, and so will vary depending on which theme you have installed and set to default. We’ll talk more about themes later. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\" alt=\"4\" width=\"314\" height=\"196\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Adding and Configuring Blocks </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\" alt=\"5\" width=\"780\" height=\"440\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-34\" /></a>\r\nTo add a block, you can click the + Add Block at the top of the page. The Add Block option allows you to enter plain text or full html, but doesn’t let you create more complicated blocks. That’s what modules are for. If you’ve enabled and properly configured a module (we’ll talk about how to do this later), if you scroll down the main Blocks page, you should be able to see blocks listed that the module has output. If you add a custom block, you should be taken back to the main blocks page.\r\n\r\nTo make a block appear on your home page, you need to place the block in a region. There are two ways to do this through the Blocks page. You can either drag the block to a region using the four way arrow, or you can select the region you wish to place it in using the drop-down menu to the right of the block’s name.\r\n\r\nTo configure a block, click on the “configure” link to the far right of the block’s name on the Blocks page. On the configure page, you can specify in what regions the block is displayed. Under visibility settings, you can choose which pages the block is displayed on, and which content types the block will be displayed for. You can also specify which Roles (Types of users) and which Users can see the block.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Types</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\" alt=\"6\" width=\"656\" height=\"297\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" /></a>\r\nHere, you can create new types of content and edit already existing content types. By default, Drupal includes the content types Article and Basic Page. Articles are typically used for more blog-like content, whereas Basic Pages are usually used for static content.\r\n\r\n<b>Editing An Already Existing Content Type</b>\r\nTo edit an already existing content type, click edit, manage fields, or manage display. Once you click on edit, manage fields, or manage display, the other links will show up as tabs when you’re editing the content type. Here, we’re on the edit tab and can see Manage Fields, Manage Display, Comment Fields, and Comment Display as other options.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\" alt=\"8\" width=\"780\" height=\"455\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-39\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>The Edit Tab</b>\r\nHere, we can set the name of the content type. We can also set submission form settings, which have to do with how content of that type will be created by a user. Publishing options let you choose whether or not the content will show up on your front page by default. \r\n\r\n<b>Manage Fields Tab</b><a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\" alt=\"9\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-42\" /></a>\r\nThis is an important part of editing a content type. Here, you get to choose what fields make up the content type. The interface here is similar to the one on the Blocks page. You can choose to add images, taxonomy, and other options as fields. Modules that you install may provide additional field types to use in your content type. You can drag the fields into different positions using the four way arrows.\r\n\r\n<b>The Manage Display Tab</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\" alt=\"10\" width=\"522\" height=\"281\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-44\" /></a>\r\nUnder manage display, you can change the way the content type is displayed when it is in a feed such as the one that appears by default on the home page.\r\n\r\n<b>Comment Fields and Comment Display</b> \r\nIf you intend to allow commenting on your site, this is where you would configure it.\r\n\r\n<b>Adding a Content Type</b>\r\nWhen you add a content type, it is very similar to editing an already existent content type. You will have to go through a series of screens, similar to the tabs, that let you fill in the options for the content types.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Menus</b>\r\nUnder menus, you can create or edit your site’s menus. These menus are a type of block and so can be placed using the Blocks page. The operations available for these menus are to list links, edit menu, and add link. Under list links, you can add, edit, and delete links from your menu. Under edit menu, you can change the name or description of your menu.\r\n </li>\r\n<li><b>Taxonomy</b>\r\nTaxonomy is a method that Drupal provides to organize content. Drupal taxonomies are made up of vocabularies. Vocabularies can be added as a field to a content type. The default vocabulary is tags, which work as one would expect. For example, you could add tags to an article just as you might add tags to a twitter post or tumblr post. \r\n\r\nYou can reorder taxonomy terms and create sub-vocabularies by dragging the taxonomy terms into different positions using the four way arrow.\r\n\r\nThere are several options given for operations allowed on vocabularies. Edit vocabularies gives you options for changing the name and description of the vocabularies. List terms lists all of the terms currently in a vocabulary and gives you options to edit or delete them.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Appearance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\" alt=\"11\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-49\" /></a>\r\nThe Appearance section is where you can set the theme for your site. All installed themes will be listed, with “Settings”, “Disable”, and “Set Default” options. Whichever theme is set as Default will be the one Drupal uses to display the pages on the site. The “Update” tab will show you when themes need to be updated, and the “Settings” tab will change settings for ALL themes on your site.\r\n\r\n<b>People </b> (Permissions are under this menu option. If something isn\'t displaying this may be why!)\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\" alt=\"12\" width=\"780\" height=\"407\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-51\" /></a>\r\nThis section has two subsections: “List” and “Permissions”. The “List” tab contains a list of all current registered users of the site with options to edit or remove accounts. \r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\" alt=\"13\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-53\" /></a>\r\nThe “Permissions” tab is more important, as it sets the permissions for various users to use different parts of the site. You will want to check this page periodically to ensure that Anonymous and/or Authenticated users are able to access functionality that may be default set to Administrator-only. In the “Permissions” tab, you can also configure Roles if you want to set more specific roles than the three provided.\r\n\r\n<b>Modules</b>\r\nModules\r\nWARNING:\r\nSome modules will completely break your website, so be cautious. Make sure that the module you’re installing has been updated fairly recently (within the last two years), that it is under active development, and that at least 1000 sites use the module. You’ll also want to make sure that the module is for Drupal 7.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\" alt=\"14\" width=\"780\" height=\"430\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-54\" /></a>\r\nThe modules section has three subsections: “List”, “Update”, and “Uninstall”. The “List” tab contains a list of all modules installed. In order to enable a module, you have to check the box next to its name, as well as enabling all the other modules it might depend on. Certain modules will also have “Permissions” and “Configure” options. It’s a good idea to check these for each module you install, and many modules will specifically guide you through their configurations. Some modules won’t do anything if you don’t correctly configure them.\r\n\r\nTo install new modules, you have two options. The first is to install the module through the GUI by clicking “Install new module”. Through this option, you can either install the module through a downloaded file from the Drupal website or by using a link to the file download. Once installed, the GUI will bring you to a page that will invite you to install new modules or to enable recently installed modules. The second is to manually install the files you’ve downloaded. To do this, you must have access to the /sites/all/modules folder of your domain. Unzip the module file in this folder, and then you will be able to enable the newly installed module through the GUI. \r\n\r\nIf you accidentally install a module that breaks everything on your site, often deleting the module from the /sites/all/modules folder will allow your site to load again.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\" alt=\"15\" width=\"780\" height=\"427\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>\r\nThe “Update” tab will tell you if any modules need updating. The “Uninstall” tab will list any modules that you have installed but disabled. If you want to uninstall any module you’ve installed, you simply have to disable it and any other modules that depend on it, and then it will appear in the “Uninstall” tab. You can uninstall it from there.\r\n\r\n<b>Configuration</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\" alt=\"16\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>\r\nThe Configuration page has many subsections for configuring various parts of the site.\r\n<ul> \r\n<li><b>People</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Account Settings</b>\r\nAccount Settings allows you to administer the settings for users signing up to your site. You can also configure the way user’s data is stored and how the profiles are displayed.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>IP Address Blocking </b>\r\nThis option allows you to block certain IP addresses, i.e., spam accounts, from accessing your site\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Authoring</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Text formats</b>\r\nThe three default text formats are sufficient for most uses, but if you need to configure the way the text of your content is read by Drupal, you can customize it here.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Media</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>File System</b>\r\nThis tells Drupal where to look for particular files. Unless you’re moving important files around, you shouldn’t need to modify this.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Styles</b>\r\nAgain, the default settings are fine for most uses here, but if you’d like to change the way particular images are displayed through the GUI, here’s where to go.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Toolkit</b>\r\nThe image toolkit allows you to adjust the default quality of images on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Search and Metadata</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Search Settings</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\" alt=\"17\" width=\"780\" height=\"422\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-62\" /></a>\r\nIn order for default search to work, it needs to be able to index your site. You can manually re-index here. You can also set the minimum number of characters to be indexed for search, whether you can search Nodes or Users, rank some content higher than others, and many more settings here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>URL Aliases</b>\r\nThis allows you to manually change certain URLs. If you will be changing many URLs, it makes sense to allow a module to do this instead. (See URL document).\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Clean URLs</b>\r\nIf you have clean URLs enabled, you will be able to remove unnecessary characters from URLs so that they simply look nicer. This does NOT necessarily make them good URLs for Search Engine Optimization, but it is a good first step.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Regional and Language</b>\r\n<ul> <li><b>Regional Settings</b>\r\nHere you may configure regional settings for default displays for time, date, etc.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Date and Time</b>\r\nAs above, this allows you to configure specifically how date and time are displayed on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>System</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Site Information</b>\r\nThis page allows you to configure various default site options such as number of posts displayed on the homepage and the URLs to the homepage and various 403/404 error pages.</li>\r\n<li><b>Actions</b>\r\nThe actions is another page that you probably won’t need to touch, but if you need to configure a specific action for a specific event on your site, go here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Cron</b>\r\nHere you can run cron manually or configure how often it is run. Cron is run when checking for updates or for reindexing your site; basically it is run anytime you need to update something on your site. It is usually enough to run Cron automatically, unless you want to manually check for specific updates (such as many new additions to your site).\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>User Interface</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Shorcuts</b>\r\nShortcuts allows you to set the shortcuts used on your Account page. This is different from the shortcuts you can set in the secondary Menu bar (the one that default reads “Add content” “Find content”). </li></ul>\r\n<li><b>Development</b> \r\n<ul><li><b>Performance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"425\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-66\" /></a>\r\nThe performance page is most useful for clearing the cache (which you will have to do so often it is probably logical to make a shortcut for it on the aforementioned Menu bar. To do this, click on “Edit shortcuts”, then add a new shortcut with the url admin/config/development/performance. This will take you directly to the performance page and will save you a lot of clicks!). This page can also help with Search Engine Optimization, as it includes bandwidth optimization settings.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Logging and Errors</b>\r\nThis allows you to set the way that Drupal can show you error messages. The default settings are usually good except in special cases.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Maintenance Mode</b>\r\nYou will want to put your site into maintenance mode if you’re going to be installing major updates or making major changes to your live site. It will provide a maintenance message to users attempting to visit the site and stop all access to the site until you turn it off.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Web Services</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>RSS Publishing</b>\r\nThis allows you to configure default settings for how your content will appear in an RSS feed.\r\n</li>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs you install more modules to your site, there may be more module-specific options under the Configuration page, but not for all modules. You can always configure modules from the Modules tab.\r\n\r\n','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 16:24:28','2014-08-14 16:24:28','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=69',0,'revision','',0),(68,1,'2014-08-14 16:23:55','2014-08-14 16:23:55','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of information that would have been helpful to us was a simple overview of what each option in Drupal\'s administration menu does. Since we were unable to find such a resource, we decided to create one ourselves.\r\n\r\n<b> Getting Started </b>\r\nThe drupal login page can be found at yoursitename.com/user.\r\nWhen you’re logged in as an administrator, you should see a black bar across the top with the options Dashboard, Content, Structure, Appearance, People, Modules, Configuration, Reports, and Help.\r\nHere’s the default Drupal home page, using the Bartik theme, as it looks when an administrator is logged in. Your site name will probably be different.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"488\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-26\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Dashboard </b>\r\nThe dashboard is not particularly important for configuring the site overall. It allows you to see some recently posted content as well as users of the site. It’s a little bit like a facebook news feed for your Drupal site, which essentially makes it useless.\r\n\r\n<b> Content </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>\r\nThis is where you can add and delete content, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<b> Stucture </b>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\" alt=\"3\" width=\"780\" height=\"457\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-31\" /></a>\r\nUnder blocks, you will find a page that lists the regions and blocks of your site. Regions are listed in bold, and are where you can assign blocks. Blocks are not in bold, and you should see a four way arrow to the left of each block title, a drop-down to the right of the title allowing you to select a region, and a “configure” link.\r\n\r\n<b>What Are Regions and Blocks?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\nBlocks are things such as content, menus, menu items, search bars, forms, widgets, and user logins. Blocks are typically the outputs of modules. Modules provide different functionalities to Drupal. We’ll talk more about modules later.\r\n\r\n<b>Regions</b>\r\nRegions are different areas of your site. If you click on Demonstrate Block Regions (just under the description on the opening Blocks page), you should see different areas of your site highlighted in yellow. These are regions, and they are essentially just different places you can put blocks. Regions are defined by the theme of your Drupal site, and so will vary depending on which theme you have installed and set to default. We’ll talk more about themes later. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\" alt=\"4\" width=\"314\" height=\"196\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Adding and Configuring Blocks </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\" alt=\"5\" width=\"780\" height=\"440\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-34\" /></a>\r\nTo add a block, you can click the + Add Block at the top of the page. The Add Block option allows you to enter plain text or full html, but doesn’t let you create more complicated blocks. That’s what modules are for. If you’ve enabled and properly configured a module (we’ll talk about how to do this later), if you scroll down the main Blocks page, you should be able to see blocks listed that the module has output. If you add a custom block, you should be taken back to the main blocks page.\r\n\r\nTo make a block appear on your home page, you need to place the block in a region. There are two ways to do this through the Blocks page. You can either drag the block to a region using the four way arrow, or you can select the region you wish to place it in using the drop-down menu to the right of the block’s name.\r\n\r\nTo configure a block, click on the “configure” link to the far right of the block’s name on the Blocks page. On the configure page, you can specify in what regions the block is displayed. Under visibility settings, you can choose which pages the block is displayed on, and which content types the block will be displayed for. You can also specify which Roles (Types of users) and which Users can see the block.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Types</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\" alt=\"6\" width=\"656\" height=\"297\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" /></a>\r\nHere, you can create new types of content and edit already existing content types. By default, Drupal includes the content types Article and Basic Page. Articles are typically used for more blog-like content, whereas Basic Pages are usually used for static content.\r\n\r\n<b>Editing An Already Existing Content Type</b>\r\nTo edit an already existing content type, click edit, manage fields, or manage display. Once you click on edit, manage fields, or manage display, the other links will show up as tabs when you’re editing the content type. Here, we’re on the edit tab and can see Manage Fields, Manage Display, Comment Fields, and Comment Display as other options.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\" alt=\"8\" width=\"780\" height=\"455\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-39\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>The Edit Tab</b>\r\nHere, we can set the name of the content type. We can also set submission form settings, which have to do with how content of that type will be created by a user. Publishing options let you choose whether or not the content will show up on your front page by default. \r\n\r\n<b>Manage Fields Tab</b><a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\" alt=\"9\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-42\" /></a>\r\nThis is an important part of editing a content type. Here, you get to choose what fields make up the content type. The interface here is similar to the one on the Blocks page. You can choose to add images, taxonomy, and other options as fields. Modules that you install may provide additional field types to use in your content type. You can drag the fields into different positions using the four way arrows.\r\n\r\n<b>The Manage Display Tab</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\" alt=\"10\" width=\"522\" height=\"281\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-44\" /></a>\r\nUnder manage display, you can change the way the content type is displayed when it is in a feed such as the one that appears by default on the home page.\r\n\r\n<b>Comment Fields and Comment Display</b> \r\nIf you intend to allow commenting on your site, this is where you would configure it.\r\n\r\n<b>Adding a Content Type</b>\r\nWhen you add a content type, it is very similar to editing an already existent content type. You will have to go through a series of screens, similar to the tabs, that let you fill in the options for the content types.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Menus</b>\r\nUnder menus, you can create or edit your site’s menus. These menus are a type of block and so can be placed using the Blocks page. The operations available for these menus are to list links, edit menu, and add link. Under list links, you can add, edit, and delete links from your menu. Under edit menu, you can change the name or description of your menu.\r\n </li>\r\n<li><b>Taxonomy</b>\r\nTaxonomy is a method that Drupal provides to organize content. Drupal taxonomies are made up of vocabularies. Vocabularies can be added as a field to a content type. The default vocabulary is tags, which work as one would expect. For example, you could add tags to an article just as you might add tags to a twitter post or tumblr post. \r\n\r\nYou can reorder taxonomy terms and create sub-vocabularies by dragging the taxonomy terms into different positions using the four way arrow.\r\n\r\nThere are several options given for operations allowed on vocabularies. Edit vocabularies gives you options for changing the name and description of the vocabularies. List terms lists all of the terms currently in a vocabulary and gives you options to edit or delete them.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Appearance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\" alt=\"11\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-49\" /></a>\r\nThe Appearance section is where you can set the theme for your site. All installed themes will be listed, with “Settings”, “Disable”, and “Set Default” options. Whichever theme is set as Default will be the one Drupal uses to display the pages on the site. The “Update” tab will show you when themes need to be updated, and the “Settings” tab will change settings for ALL themes on your site.\r\n\r\n<b>People </b> (Permissions are under this menu option. If something isn\'t displaying this may be why!)\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\" alt=\"12\" width=\"780\" height=\"407\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-51\" /></a>\r\nThis section has two subsections: “List” and “Permissions”. The “List” tab contains a list of all current registered users of the site with options to edit or remove accounts. \r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\" alt=\"13\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-53\" /></a>\r\nThe “Permissions” tab is more important, as it sets the permissions for various users to use different parts of the site. You will want to check this page periodically to ensure that Anonymous and/or Authenticated users are able to access functionality that may be default set to Administrator-only. In the “Permissions” tab, you can also configure Roles if you want to set more specific roles than the three provided.\r\n\r\n<b>Modules</b>\r\nModules\r\nWARNING:\r\nSome modules will completely break your website, so be cautious. Make sure that the module you’re installing has been updated fairly recently (within the last two years), that it is under active development, and that at least 1000 sites use the module. You’ll also want to make sure that the module is for Drupal 7.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\" alt=\"14\" width=\"780\" height=\"430\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-54\" /></a>\r\nThe modules section has three subsections: “List”, “Update”, and “Uninstall”. The “List” tab contains a list of all modules installed. In order to enable a module, you have to check the box next to its name, as well as enabling all the other modules it might depend on. Certain modules will also have “Permissions” and “Configure” options. It’s a good idea to check these for each module you install, and many modules will specifically guide you through their configurations. Some modules won’t do anything if you don’t correctly configure them.\r\n\r\nTo install new modules, you have two options. The first is to install the module through the GUI by clicking “Install new module”. Through this option, you can either install the module through a downloaded file from the Drupal website or by using a link to the file download. Once installed, the GUI will bring you to a page that will invite you to install new modules or to enable recently installed modules. The second is to manually install the files you’ve downloaded. To do this, you must have access to the /sites/all/modules folder of your domain. Unzip the module file in this folder, and then you will be able to enable the newly installed module through the GUI. \r\n\r\nIf you accidentally install a module that breaks everything on your site, often deleting the module from the /sites/all/modules folder will allow your site to load again.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\" alt=\"15\" width=\"780\" height=\"427\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>\r\nThe “Update” tab will tell you if any modules need updating. The “Uninstall” tab will list any modules that you have installed but disabled. If you want to uninstall any module you’ve installed, you simply have to disable it and any other modules that depend on it, and then it will appear in the “Uninstall” tab. You can uninstall it from there.\r\n\r\n<b>Configuration</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\" alt=\"16\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>\r\nThe Configuration page has many subsections for configuring various parts of the site.\r\n<ul> \r\n<li><b>People</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Account Settings</b>\r\nAccount Settings allows you to administer the settings for users signing up to your site. You can also configure the way user’s data is stored and how the profiles are displayed.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>IP Address Blocking </b>\r\nThis option allows you to block certain IP addresses, i.e., spam accounts, from accessing your site\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Authoring</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Text formats</b>\r\nThe three default text formats are sufficient for most uses, but if you need to configure the way the text of your content is read by Drupal, you can customize it here.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Media</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>File System</b>\r\nThis tells Drupal where to look for particular files. Unless you’re moving important files around, you shouldn’t need to modify this.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Styles</b>\r\nAgain, the default settings are fine for most uses here, but if you’d like to change the way particular images are displayed through the GUI, here’s where to go.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Toolkit</b>\r\nThe image toolkit allows you to adjust the default quality of images on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Search and Metadata</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Search Settings</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\" alt=\"17\" width=\"780\" height=\"422\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-62\" /></a>\r\nIn order for default search to work, it needs to be able to index your site. You can manually re-index here. You can also set the minimum number of characters to be indexed for search, whether you can search Nodes or Users, rank some content higher than others, and many more settings here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>URL Aliases</b>\r\nThis allows you to manually change certain URLs. If you will be changing many URLs, it makes sense to allow a module to do this instead. (See URL document).\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Clean URLs</b>\r\nIf you have clean URLs enabled, you will be able to remove unnecessary characters from URLs so that they simply look nicer. This does NOT necessarily make them good URLs for Search Engine Optimization, but it is a good first step.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Regional and Language</b>\r\n<ul> <li><b>Regional Settings</b>\r\nHere you may configure regional settings for default displays for time, date, etc.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Date and Time</b>\r\nAs above, this allows you to configure specifically how date and time are displayed on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>System</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Site Information</b>\r\nThis page allows you to configure various default site options such as number of posts displayed on the homepage and the URLs to the homepage and various 403/404 error pages.</li>\r\n<li><b>Actions</b>\r\nThe actions is another page that you probably won’t need to touch, but if you need to configure a specific action for a specific event on your site, go here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Cron</b>\r\nHere you can run cron manually or configure how often it is run. Cron is run when checking for updates or for reindexing your site; basically it is run anytime you need to update something on your site. It is usually enough to run Cron automatically, unless you want to manually check for specific updates (such as many new additions to your site).\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>User Interface</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Shorcuts</b>\r\nShortcuts allows you to set the shortcuts used on your Account page. This is different from the shortcuts you can set in the secondary Menu bar (the one that default reads “Add content” “Find content”). </li></ul>\r\n<li><b>Development</b> \r\n<ul><li><b>Performance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"425\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-66\" /></a>\r\nThe performance page is most useful for clearing the cache (which you will have to do so often it is probably logical to make a shortcut for it on the aforementioned Menu bar. To do this, click on “Edit shortcuts”, then add a new shortcut with the url admin/config/development/performance. This will take you directly to the performance page and will save you a lot of clicks!). This page can also help with Search Engine Optimization, as it includes bandwidth optimization settings.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Logging and Errors</b>\r\nThis allows you to set the way that Drupal can show you error messages. The default settings are usually good except in special cases.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Maintenance Mode</b>\r\nYou will want to put your site into maintenance mode if you’re going to be installing major updates or making major changes to your live site. It will provide a maintenance message to users attempting to visit the site and stop all access to the site until you turn it off.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Web Services</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>RSS Publishing</b>\r\nThis allows you to configure default settings for how your content will appear in an RSS feed.\r\n</li>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>As you install more modules to your site, there may be more module-specific options under the Configuration page, but not for all modules. You can always configure modules from the Modules tab.</li>\r\n\r\n','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 16:23:55','2014-08-14 16:23:55','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=68',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2014-08-14 16:27:14','2014-08-14 16:27:14','','3','','inherit','open','open','','3-2','','','2014-08-14 16:27:14','2014-08-14 16:27:14','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/31.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(73,1,'2014-08-14 16:27:31','2014-08-14 16:27:31','Once our team decided that Drupal was our CMS (Content Management System) of choice, our first challenge was learning how to use the Drupal GUI (Graphical User Interface). This may seem like it would be an extremely simple task. That appearance of simplicity is somewhat deceiving.\r\n\r\nWhile there is Drupal documentation available both on <a href = \"https://drupal.org\"> drupal.org </a> and in other places on the internet, we found that helpful documentation was difficult to find. Either it was for a previous version of Drupal, was incomplete, or simply didn\'t tell us what we wanted to know.\r\n\r\nOne collection of information that would have been helpful to us was a simple overview of what each option in Drupal\'s administration menu does. Since we were unable to find such a resource, we decided to create one ourselves.\r\n\r\n<b> Getting Started </b>\r\nThe drupal login page can be found at yoursitename.com/user.\r\nWhen you’re logged in as an administrator, you should see a black bar across the top with the options Dashboard, Content, Structure, Appearance, People, Modules, Configuration, Reports, and Help.\r\nHere’s the default Drupal home page, using the Bartik theme, as it looks when an administrator is logged in. Your site name will probably be different.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/1.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"488\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-26\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Dashboard </b>\r\nThe dashboard is not particularly important for configuring the site overall. It allows you to see some recently posted content as well as users of the site. It’s a little bit like a facebook news feed for your Drupal site, which essentially makes it useless.\r\n\r\n<b> Content </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/2.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"584\" height=\"246\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-27\" /></a>\r\nThis is where you can add and delete content, or “nodes”, as Drupal calls them. By default, Drupal has two different content types - articles and basic pages. It is also possible to create custom content types, which will be discussed later. You can create content of different types under this menu option. Types are defined and created under the structure menu. You will also see a list of all the content that has been previously created on the site, if any.\r\nYou will also see a comments tab, which is only important if your site has comments enabled.\r\n\r\n<b> Stucture </b>\r\nThis is one of the most important menus on the site. Under structure, you will find these options:\r\n<ul> \r\n<li>\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/3.png\" alt=\"3\" width=\"780\" height=\"457\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-31\" /></a>\r\nUnder blocks, you will find a page that lists the regions and blocks of your site. Regions are listed in bold, and are where you can assign blocks. Blocks are not in bold, and you should see a four way arrow to the left of each block title, a drop-down to the right of the title allowing you to select a region, and a “configure” link.\r\n\r\n<b>What Are Regions and Blocks?</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Blocks</b>\r\nBlocks are things such as content, menus, menu items, search bars, forms, widgets, and user logins. Blocks are typically the outputs of modules. Modules provide different functionalities to Drupal. We’ll talk more about modules later.\r\n\r\n<b>Regions</b>\r\nRegions are different areas of your site. If you click on Demonstrate Block Regions (just under the description on the opening Blocks page), you should see different areas of your site highlighted in yellow. These are regions, and they are essentially just different places you can put blocks. Regions are defined by the theme of your Drupal site, and so will vary depending on which theme you have installed and set to default. We’ll talk more about themes later. \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/4.png\" alt=\"4\" width=\"314\" height=\"196\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-32\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b> Adding and Configuring Blocks </b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/5.png\" alt=\"5\" width=\"780\" height=\"440\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-34\" /></a>\r\nTo add a block, you can click the + Add Block at the top of the page. The Add Block option allows you to enter plain text or full html, but doesn’t let you create more complicated blocks. That’s what modules are for. If you’ve enabled and properly configured a module (we’ll talk about how to do this later), if you scroll down the main Blocks page, you should be able to see blocks listed that the module has output. If you add a custom block, you should be taken back to the main blocks page.\r\n\r\nTo make a block appear on your home page, you need to place the block in a region. There are two ways to do this through the Blocks page. You can either drag the block to a region using the four way arrow, or you can select the region you wish to place it in using the drop-down menu to the right of the block’s name.\r\n\r\nTo configure a block, click on the “configure” link to the far right of the block’s name on the Blocks page. On the configure page, you can specify in what regions the block is displayed. Under visibility settings, you can choose which pages the block is displayed on, and which content types the block will be displayed for. You can also specify which Roles (Types of users) and which Users can see the block.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Types</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/6.png\" alt=\"6\" width=\"656\" height=\"297\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" /></a>\r\nHere, you can create new types of content and edit already existing content types. By default, Drupal includes the content types Article and Basic Page. Articles are typically used for more blog-like content, whereas Basic Pages are usually used for static content.\r\n\r\n<b>Editing An Already Existing Content Type</b>\r\nTo edit an already existing content type, click edit, manage fields, or manage display. Once you click on edit, manage fields, or manage display, the other links will show up as tabs when you’re editing the content type. Here, we’re on the edit tab and can see Manage Fields, Manage Display, Comment Fields, and Comment Display as other options.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/8.png\" alt=\"8\" width=\"780\" height=\"455\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-39\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<b>The Edit Tab</b>\r\nHere, we can set the name of the content type. We can also set submission form settings, which have to do with how content of that type will be created by a user. Publishing options let you choose whether or not the content will show up on your front page by default. \r\n\r\n<b>Manage Fields Tab</b><a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/9.png\" alt=\"9\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-42\" /></a>\r\nThis is an important part of editing a content type. Here, you get to choose what fields make up the content type. The interface here is similar to the one on the Blocks page. You can choose to add images, taxonomy, and other options as fields. Modules that you install may provide additional field types to use in your content type. You can drag the fields into different positions using the four way arrows.\r\n\r\n<b>The Manage Display Tab</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10.png\" alt=\"10\" width=\"522\" height=\"281\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-44\" /></a>\r\nUnder manage display, you can change the way the content type is displayed when it is in a feed such as the one that appears by default on the home page.\r\n\r\n<b>Comment Fields and Comment Display</b> \r\nIf you intend to allow commenting on your site, this is where you would configure it.\r\n\r\n<b>Adding a Content Type</b>\r\nWhen you add a content type, it is very similar to editing an already existent content type. You will have to go through a series of screens, similar to the tabs, that let you fill in the options for the content types.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Menus</b>\r\nUnder menus, you can create or edit your site’s menus. These menus are a type of block and so can be placed using the Blocks page. The operations available for these menus are to list links, edit menu, and add link. Under list links, you can add, edit, and delete links from your menu. Under edit menu, you can change the name or description of your menu.\r\n </li>\r\n<li><b>Taxonomy</b>\r\nTaxonomy is a method that Drupal provides to organize content. Drupal taxonomies are made up of vocabularies. Vocabularies can be added as a field to a content type. The default vocabulary is tags, which work as one would expect. For example, you could add tags to an article just as you might add tags to a twitter post or tumblr post. \r\n\r\nYou can reorder taxonomy terms and create sub-vocabularies by dragging the taxonomy terms into different positions using the four way arrow.\r\n\r\nThere are several options given for operations allowed on vocabularies. Edit vocabularies gives you options for changing the name and description of the vocabularies. List terms lists all of the terms currently in a vocabulary and gives you options to edit or delete them.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Appearance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/11.png\" alt=\"11\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-49\" /></a>\r\nThe Appearance section is where you can set the theme for your site. All installed themes will be listed, with “Settings”, “Disable”, and “Set Default” options. Whichever theme is set as Default will be the one Drupal uses to display the pages on the site. The “Update” tab will show you when themes need to be updated, and the “Settings” tab will change settings for ALL themes on your site.\r\n\r\n<b>People </b> (Permissions are under this menu option. If something isn\'t displaying this may be why!)\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/12.png\" alt=\"12\" width=\"780\" height=\"407\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-51\" /></a>\r\nThis section has two subsections: “List” and “Permissions”. The “List” tab contains a list of all current registered users of the site with options to edit or remove accounts. \r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/13.png\" alt=\"13\" width=\"780\" height=\"418\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-53\" /></a>\r\nThe “Permissions” tab is more important, as it sets the permissions for various users to use different parts of the site. You will want to check this page periodically to ensure that Anonymous and/or Authenticated users are able to access functionality that may be default set to Administrator-only. In the “Permissions” tab, you can also configure Roles if you want to set more specific roles than the three provided.\r\n\r\n<b>Modules</b>\r\nModules\r\nWARNING:\r\nSome modules will completely break your website, so be cautious. Make sure that the module you’re installing has been updated fairly recently (within the last two years), that it is under active development, and that at least 1000 sites use the module. You’ll also want to make sure that the module is for Drupal 7.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/14.png\" alt=\"14\" width=\"780\" height=\"430\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-54\" /></a>\r\nThe modules section has three subsections: “List”, “Update”, and “Uninstall”. The “List” tab contains a list of all modules installed. In order to enable a module, you have to check the box next to its name, as well as enabling all the other modules it might depend on. Certain modules will also have “Permissions” and “Configure” options. It’s a good idea to check these for each module you install, and many modules will specifically guide you through their configurations. Some modules won’t do anything if you don’t correctly configure them.\r\n\r\nTo install new modules, you have two options. The first is to install the module through the GUI by clicking “Install new module”. Through this option, you can either install the module through a downloaded file from the Drupal website or by using a link to the file download. Once installed, the GUI will bring you to a page that will invite you to install new modules or to enable recently installed modules. The second is to manually install the files you’ve downloaded. To do this, you must have access to the /sites/all/modules folder of your domain. Unzip the module file in this folder, and then you will be able to enable the newly installed module through the GUI. \r\n\r\nIf you accidentally install a module that breaks everything on your site, often deleting the module from the /sites/all/modules folder will allow your site to load again.\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/15.png\" alt=\"15\" width=\"780\" height=\"427\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>\r\nThe “Update” tab will tell you if any modules need updating. The “Uninstall” tab will list any modules that you have installed but disabled. If you want to uninstall any module you’ve installed, you simply have to disable it and any other modules that depend on it, and then it will appear in the “Uninstall” tab. You can uninstall it from there.\r\n\r\n<b>Configuration</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/16.png\" alt=\"16\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>\r\nThe Configuration page has many subsections for configuring various parts of the site.\r\n<ul> \r\n<li><b>People</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Account Settings</b>\r\nAccount Settings allows you to administer the settings for users signing up to your site. You can also configure the way user’s data is stored and how the profiles are displayed.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>IP Address Blocking </b>\r\nThis option allows you to block certain IP addresses, i.e., spam accounts, from accessing your site\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Content Authoring</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Text formats</b>\r\nThe three default text formats are sufficient for most uses, but if you need to configure the way the text of your content is read by Drupal, you can customize it here.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Media</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>File System</b>\r\nThis tells Drupal where to look for particular files. Unless you’re moving important files around, you shouldn’t need to modify this.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Styles</b>\r\nAgain, the default settings are fine for most uses here, but if you’d like to change the way particular images are displayed through the GUI, here’s where to go.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Image Toolkit</b>\r\nThe image toolkit allows you to adjust the default quality of images on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Search and Metadata</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><b>Search Settings</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/17.png\" alt=\"17\" width=\"780\" height=\"422\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-62\" /></a>\r\nIn order for default search to work, it needs to be able to index your site. You can manually re-index here. You can also set the minimum number of characters to be indexed for search, whether you can search Nodes or Users, rank some content higher than others, and many more settings here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>URL Aliases</b>\r\nThis allows you to manually change certain URLs. If you will be changing many URLs, it makes sense to allow a module to do this instead. (See URL document).\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Clean URLs</b>\r\nIf you have clean URLs enabled, you will be able to remove unnecessary characters from URLs so that they simply look nicer. This does NOT necessarily make them good URLs for Search Engine Optimization, but it is a good first step.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Regional and Language</b>\r\n<ul> <li><b>Regional Settings</b>\r\nHere you may configure regional settings for default displays for time, date, etc.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Date and Time</b>\r\nAs above, this allows you to configure specifically how date and time are displayed on your site.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>System</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Site Information</b>\r\nThis page allows you to configure various default site options such as number of posts displayed on the homepage and the URLs to the homepage and various 403/404 error pages.</li>\r\n<li><b>Actions</b>\r\nThe actions is another page that you probably won’t need to touch, but if you need to configure a specific action for a specific event on your site, go here.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Cron</b>\r\nHere you can run cron manually or configure how often it is run. Cron is run when checking for updates or for reindexing your site; basically it is run anytime you need to update something on your site. It is usually enough to run Cron automatically, unless you want to manually check for specific updates (such as many new additions to your site).\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>User Interface</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>Shorcuts</b>\r\nShortcuts allows you to set the shortcuts used on your Account page. This is different from the shortcuts you can set in the secondary Menu bar (the one that default reads “Add content” “Find content”). </li></ul>\r\n<li><b>Development</b> \r\n<ul><li><b>Performance</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/18.png\" alt=\"1\" width=\"780\" height=\"425\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-66\" /></a>\r\nThe performance page is most useful for clearing the cache (which you will have to do so often it is probably logical to make a shortcut for it on the aforementioned Menu bar. To do this, click on “Edit shortcuts”, then add a new shortcut with the url admin/config/development/performance. This will take you directly to the performance page and will save you a lot of clicks!). This page can also help with Search Engine Optimization, as it includes bandwidth optimization settings.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Logging and Errors</b>\r\nThis allows you to set the way that Drupal can show you error messages. The default settings are usually good except in special cases.\r\n</li>\r\n<li><b>Maintenance Mode</b>\r\nYou will want to put your site into maintenance mode if you’re going to be installing major updates or making major changes to your live site. It will provide a maintenance message to users attempting to visit the site and stop all access to the site until you turn it off.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li><b>Web Services</b>\r\n<ul><li><b>RSS Publishing</b>\r\nThis allows you to configure default settings for how your content will appear in an RSS feed.\r\n</li>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs you install more modules to your site, there may be more module-specific options under the Configuration page, but not for all modules. You can always configure modules from the Modules tab.\r\n<b>Reports</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/21.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/21.png\" alt=\"2\" width=\"780\" height=\"430\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-71\" /></a>\r\nThe reports page contains a list of links of status reports and updates for your site. This can be helpful for monitoring how users are using your site. It also includes a Field list, which lists all fields currently in use. This page also will tell you about necessary updates for all your files.\r\n<b>Help</b>\r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/31.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/31.png\" alt=\"3\" width=\"780\" height=\"428\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-72\" /></a>\r\nThe help page has many links explaining different parts of your Drupal installation. As a general rule, it is usually easier to find the answer you’re looking for from other developers on the web rather than in Drupal’s documentation.\r\n','Learning the Drupal GUI','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 16:27:31','2014-08-14 16:27:31','',16,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=73',0,'revision','',0),(74,1,'2014-08-14 17:06:15','2014-08-14 17:06:15','<b>1. Have you cleared the cache?</b>\r\n\r\nIf you haven’t, do it. I don’t care if you think this won’t help, do it anyway. 90% of the time this fixes the problem. Also, 70% of all statistics are true.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to Clear the Cache</b></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login to your site as an administrator.</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Configuration → Performance</li>\r\n	<li>Click the “Clear Cache” button. It may take a little while for the cache to clear.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>2. Do you have the correct theme set as default?</b>\r\n\r\nA lot of changes made through the GUI (and through template files/css) are theme-specific. If you made a change when a different theme was set as default, you may not be seeing those changes.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to change your theme</b></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login to your site as an administrator</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Appearance</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the correct theme is set as default.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>3. Do you have the correct permissions?</b>\r\n\r\nIf you make changes and can only see them when you’re logged in to the site, this is probably the problem.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to change permissions</b></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Go to People and click on the permissions tab.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure that the appropriate user has permission to see whatever you made a change to.</li>\r\n</ul>','Drupal: Why don\'t my changes appear?','','publish','open','open','','drupal-why-dont-my-changes-appear','','','2014-08-14 17:06:15','2014-08-14 17:06:15','',0,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=74',0,'post','',0),(79,1,'2014-08-14 17:05:58','2014-08-14 17:05:58','<b>1. Have you cleared the cache?</b>\r\n\r\nIf you haven’t, do it. I don’t care if you think this won’t help, do it anyway. 90% of the time this fixes the problem. Also, 70% of all statistics are true.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to Clear the Cache</b></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login to your site as an administrator.</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Configuration → Performance</li>\r\n	<li>Click the “Clear Cache” button. It may take a little while for the cache to clear.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>2. Do you have the correct theme set as default?</b>\r\n\r\nA lot of changes made through the GUI (and through template files/css) are theme-specific. If you made a change when a different theme was set as default, you may not be seeing those changes.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to change your theme</b></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login to your site as an administrator</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Appearance</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the correct theme is set as default.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>3. Do you have the correct permissions?</b>\r\n\r\nIf you make changes and can only see them when you’re logged in to the site, this is probably the problem.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to change permissions</b></b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Go to People and click on the permissions tab.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure that the appropriate user has permission to see whatever you made a change to.</li>\r\n</ul>','Drupal: Why don\'t my changes appear?','','inherit','open','open','','74-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 17:05:58','2014-08-14 17:05:58','',74,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=79',0,'revision','',0),(78,1,'2014-08-14 17:05:23','2014-08-14 17:05:23','<b>1. Have you cleared the cache?</b>\r\n\r\nIf you haven’t, do it. I don’t care if you think this won’t help, do it anyway. 90% of the time this fixes the problem. Also, 70% of all statistics are true.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to Clear the Cache</b></b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login to your site as an administrator.</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Configuration → Performance</li>\r\n	<li>Click the “Clear Cache” button. It may take a little while for the cache to clear.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>2. Do you have the correct theme set as default?</b>\r\n\r\nA lot of changes made through the GUI (and through template files/css) are theme-specific. If you made a change when a different theme was set as default, you may not be seeing those changes.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to change your theme</b></b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Login to your site as an administrator</li>\r\n	<li>Go to Appearance</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the correct theme is set as default.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>3. Do you have the correct permissions?</b>\r\n\r\nIf you make changes and can only see them when you’re logged in to the site, this is probably the problem.\r\n\r\n<b><b>How to change permissions</b></b>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Go to People and click on the permissions tab.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure that the appropriate user has permission to see whatever you made a change to.</li>\r\n</ul>','Drupal: Why don\'t my changes appear?','','inherit','open','open','','74-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 17:05:23','2014-08-14 17:05:23','',74,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=78',0,'revision','',0),(75,1,'2014-08-14 16:59:22','2014-08-14 16:59:22','In our adventures with Drupal, we sometimes noticed that changes we made didn\'t appear as we would have expected. There\'s usually a simple fix. Here\'s a list of the three most common reasons we encountered for changes not appearing on our Drupal site.\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Have you cleared the cache?</b>\r\nIf you haven’t, do it. I don’t care if you think this won’t help, do it anyway. 90% of the time this fixes the problem. Also, 70% of all statistics are true.\r\nHow to Clear the Cache\r\nLogin to your site as an administrator.\r\nGo to Configuration → Performance\r\nClick the “Clear Cache” button. It may take a little while for the cache to clear.\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Do you have the correct theme set as default?</b>\r\nA lot of changes made through the GUI (and through template files/css) are theme-specific. If you made a change when a different theme was set as default, you may not be seeing those changes.\r\nHow to change your theme\r\nLogin to your site as an administrator\r\nGo to Appearance\r\nMake sure the correct theme is set as default. \r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Do you have the correct permissions?</b>\r\nIf you make changes and can only see them when you’re logged in to the site, this is probably the problem. \r\nHow to change permissions\r\nGo to People and click on the permissions tab.\r\nMake sure that the appropriate user has permission to see whatever you made a change to.\r\n</li>','Drupal: Why don\'t my changes appear?','','inherit','open','open','','74-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 16:59:22','2014-08-14 16:59:22','',74,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=75',0,'revision','',0),(76,1,'2014-08-14 17:02:48','2014-08-14 17:02:48','In our adventures with Drupal, we sometimes noticed that changes we made didn\'t appear as we would have expected. There\'s usually a simple fix. Here\'s a list of the three most common reasons we encountered for changes not appearing on our Drupal site.\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Have you cleared the cache?</b>\r\nIf you haven’t, do it. I don’t care if you think this won’t help, do it anyway. 90% of the time this fixes the problem. Also, 70% of all statistics are true.\r\n<ul><li><b>How to Clear the Cache</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Login to your site as an administrator.</li>\r\n<li>Go to Configuration → Performance</li>\r\n<li>Click the “Clear Cache” button. It may take a little while for the cache to clear.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Do you have the correct theme set as default?</b>\r\nA lot of changes made through the GUI (and through template files/css) are theme-specific. If you made a change when a different theme was set as default, you may not be seeing those changes.\r\n<ul><li><b>How to change your theme</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\nLogin to your site as an administrator </li>\r\n<li>Go to Appearance</li>\r\n<li>Make sure the correct theme is set as default. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Do you have the correct permissions?</b>\r\nIf you make changes and can only see them when you’re logged in to the site, this is probably the problem. \r\nHow to change permissions\r\nGo to People and click on the permissions tab.\r\nMake sure that the appropriate user has permission to see whatever you made a change to.\r\n</li>','Drupal: Why don\'t my changes appear?','','inherit','open','open','','74-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 17:02:48','2014-08-14 17:02:48','',74,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=76',0,'revision','',0),(77,1,'2014-08-14 17:03:08','2014-08-14 17:03:08','In our adventures with Drupal, we sometimes noticed that changes we made didn\'t appear as we would have expected. There\'s usually a simple fix. Here\'s a list of the three most common reasons we encountered for changes not appearing on our Drupal site.\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Have you cleared the cache?</b>\r\nIf you haven’t, do it. I don’t care if you think this won’t help, do it anyway. 90% of the time this fixes the problem. Also, 70% of all statistics are true.\r\n<ul><li><b>How to Clear the Cache</b><ul>\r\n<li>Login to your site as an administrator.</li>\r\n<li>Go to Configuration → Performance</li>\r\n<li>Click the “Clear Cache” button. It may take a little while for the cache to clear.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Do you have the correct theme set as default?</b>\r\nA lot of changes made through the GUI (and through template files/css) are theme-specific. If you made a change when a different theme was set as default, you may not be seeing those changes.\r\n<ul><li><b>How to change your theme</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\nLogin to your site as an administrator </li>\r\n<li>Go to Appearance</li>\r\n<li>Make sure the correct theme is set as default. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\n<b>Do you have the correct permissions?</b>\r\nIf you make changes and can only see them when you’re logged in to the site, this is probably the problem. \r\nHow to change permissions\r\nGo to People and click on the permissions tab.\r\nMake sure that the appropriate user has permission to see whatever you made a change to.\r\n</li>','Drupal: Why don\'t my changes appear?','','inherit','open','open','','74-revision-v1','','','2014-08-14 17:03:08','2014-08-14 17:03:08','',74,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=77',0,'revision','',0),(80,1,'2014-08-14 18:01:55','2014-08-14 18:01:55','If you want to make changes to the appearance of your Drupal site that you can’t make through the GUI or by using custom CSS in a theme, you may want to make custom template files. Template files control the way every piece of content on your Drupal site displays. If you wanted to completely ignore the way Drupal is supposed to be used and overwrite everything with custom html, this is how you would do it.\r\n\r\nDrupal will recognize and use properly named custom template files in a theme or subtheme instead of the default template files. Never directly modify the default template files. Instead, create either a custom theme or a sub-theme. If you want to base your theme off of an already existent theme, you should create a sub-theme. There is a documentation page <a href = \"https://www.drupal.org/node/225125\">here</a> that gives detailed instructions on how to create a sub-theme.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a custom theme or sub-theme, you can start to override Drupal’s default template files.\r\n\r\nIn your theme (which should be located at sites/all/themes/your_subtheme_name), create a folder called “templates”. It’s important that you follow this naming convention in order for Drupal to recognize your template files.\r\n\r\nDrupal template files all end with the extension .tpl.php and typically contain a mixture of html and php.\r\n\r\nThe naming schemes for different types of template overrides are given <a href =\"https://www.drupal.org/node/1089656\">here</a>. You can use template overrides for different content types, or even specific nodes. In order for your override to be seen, it is key that you use the correct naming scheme and that you have created content of the correct type.\r\n\r\nTo start out, it’s a good idea to copy the default template files into your theme. Drupal’s default page.tpl.php and html.tpl.php files can be found in modules/system. You can similarly find the default block.tpl.php in modules/block. Once you’ve copied these files into your theme, any changes you make to them will override the default files.\r\n\r\nThe default page template, page.tpl.php, by default affects all of the pages on your site. It controls things such as menus, navigation, and what content is displayed. For example, if you delete everything in the copy of page.tpl.php in your theme and replace it with “Hello World”, that’s what will show up on every page of your site (This is probably not what you want).\r\n\r\nThe default block template, block.tpl.php, affects the way that blocks look on your site. Blocks are output by Drupal modules. Examples of different blocks include the default search bar and the user login. You can see a complete list of default blocks in structure→blocks when you log into your site. You can also assign blocks to different regions of your page. Regions are how Drupal knows where to put different blocks. Regions are defined in your theme’s .info file.\r\n\r\nNode template files can be used to theme different content types. New content types can be created in the administration interface. There are a number of other possible overrides, which are given in the Drupal documentation page on custom theme hooks.\r\n\r\nIn a custom template file with the correct naming scheme, you can use a mixture of custom php and html to precisely control the way parts of your site are displayed. One thing that may be useful is to be able to print blocks in a template file.\r\n\r\nTo print blocks in a custom .tpl.php template such as page.tpl.php: \r\nPrinting only content of a block: \r\n<pre>\r\n<?php $block = module_invoke(module, hook, delta);\r\nprint render ($block[‘content’]); ?>\r\n</pre><br>\r\nPrint the entire block:\r\n<pre>\r\n<?php $block = block_load(module, delta);\r\n$blocktorender = _block_get_renderable_array(_block_render_blocks(array($block));\r\nprint drupal_render($blocktorender); ?>\r\n</pre><br>\r\n\r\n\r\nFor both of these code snippets, module is the name of the module producing the block, hook is the hook that needs to be invoked in the module, and delta is what identifies the block. The hook can be found by determining the block’s machine name, which can usually be found in whatever module you used to create the block. The delta can be found by going to structure → blocks in the administration interface and hovering over the “configure” link for the block. The url should appear in the bottom left hand corner of your screen. The part of the url right before /configure will be the block’s delta. For example, in the url \r\nhttp://localhost:8888/public_html/user/1#overlay=admin/structure/block/manage/views/similar_tips-block/configure\r\nsimilar_tips-block would be the block’s delta.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Custom Page Templates in Drupal','','draft','open','open','','','','','2014-08-14 18:17:07','2014-08-14 18:17:07','',0,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=80',0,'post','',0),(82,1,'2014-08-14 17:47:12','2014-08-14 17:47:12','If you want to make changes to the appearance of your Drupal site that you can’t make through the GUI or by using custom CSS in a theme, you may want to make custom template files. Template files control the way every piece of content on your Drupal site displays. If you wanted to completely ignore the way Drupal is supposed to be used and overwrite everything with custom html, this is how you would do it.\r\n\r\nDrupal will recognize and use properly named custom template files in a theme or subtheme instead of the default template files. Never directly modify the default template files. Instead, create either a custom theme or a sub-theme. If you want to base your theme off of an already existent theme, you should create a sub-theme. There is a documentation page <a href = \"https://www.drupal.org/node/225125\">here</a> that gives detailed instructions on how to create a sub-theme.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a custom theme or sub-theme, you can start to override Drupal’s default template files.\r\n\r\nIn your theme (which should be located at sites/all/themes/your_subtheme_name), create a folder called “templates”. It’s important that you follow this naming convention in order for Drupal to recognize your template files.\r\n\r\nDrupal template files all end with the extension .tpl.php and typically contain a mixture of html and php.\r\n\r\nThe namin