e the way the home page displays content by default in Drupal, then Views is for you!\r\n\r\nOne of the most important things to realize when using views is that settings are not always where you’d expect them to be. Almost everything that’s a link on the edit view page gives you some form of settings. If you can’t at first find the setting you’re looking for, keep clicking things or ask the internet.\r\n\r\nOnce you’ve installed Views, you can configure it by logging into your site as an administrator and going to Structure → Views.\r\n\r\nYou should see this: \r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/41.png\"><img s<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/52.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/52.png\" alt=\"5\" width=\"780\" height=\"440\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-89\" /></a>\r\nView name lets you choose a name for your new view.\r\nThe dropdowns in the line “Show content of type all tagged with ______ sorted by newest first” allows you to choose what will be displayed in your view.\r\n\r\nYou are give the options to create a page or a block. A block can be displayed in a region on your site, and does not require a path. A page on the other hand will create a new page on your site with a new path.\r\n\r\nLet’s select create a page. Under create a page, we’re given some options about how the view will be displayed. Give your page a title and a path. Then, click the continue & edit button. \r\n\r\nNow, we’re getting to the meat of the Views module.\r\nYou will see this screen. \r\n<a href=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/61.png\"><img src=\"http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/61.png\" alt=\"6\" width=\"780\" height=\"424\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-90\" /></a>\r\n\r\nTITLE\r\nUnder title, you can change the title of the view. Here, it’s set to example.\r\n\r\nFORMAT\r\n\r\nFormat: Unformatted list | Settings\r\nIf you click on Unformatted list, you’ll be given some options about how the view will be styled.\r\nIf you click on Settings, you’ll be given more options for how the view will be styled.\r\n\r\nShow: Content | Teaser \r\nIf you click Content, you’ll be given options for what you want your view to display. If you select fields, you’ll be able to customize them under FIELDS. If you click on Teaser, you’ll be given options about the style of how the content is displayed.\r\n\r\nFIELDS\r\nIf you have a view that displays fields, you will see an “add” button. If you click on that, you’ll be given the option to add different fields to your view. Once you’ve added a field, you can click on it to see more settings.\r\n\r\nFILTER CRITERIA\r\nHere, you can set up filters to limit what content is displayed in your view. Once you’ve created a filter, you can click on it for detailed settings. You can also get more settings if you click on the settings link.\r\n\r\nIf you click on the filter name, you will see a checkbox that says “expose filter to visitors”. This allows you to create filters on your view so that viewers can limit the content that they’re seeing.\r\n\r\nSORT CRITERIA\r\nSort criteria affect the order in which your content appears in your view. There is an option to expose the sort order to visitors, but it has a downside. Views currently has a bug when multiple sort criteria are used - it will only use the sort order at the top of the list, regardless of what the user may have selected.\r\n\r\nPAGE SETTINGS\r\nHere, you can set a path to your view. If your view is a block, you won’t be able to set a path to it.\r\nIf you want a link to your view to appear in a menu on your site, you can set that under menu.\r\nAccess allows you to choose which users will be able to see your view.\r\n\r\nPAGER\r\nIf you have a lot of content, you may want to use a pager. This allows your view to be split up into multiple pages of however much content you want per page.\r\n\r\nAdvanced Settings:\r\nHere we’re going to look at a few of View’s advanced settings. \r\n\r\nEXPOSED FORM\r\nIf you want to expose filters to your users in a block elsewhere on the site and have that block point to your view, you can do so by setting “Expose form in a block” to yes. Once you’ve enabled this, if you go to structure→Blocks, you should see a block for your view in the list.\r\n\r\nOTHER\r\nOne of the most valuable parts of the views module is hidden at the bottom of the OTHER section. That is Theme: information. If you want to create custom templates for your view to make it look the way you want it to, this information is extremely valuable.\r\nHere, it will tell you which files the view is getting its theming from, and it will also suggest names for overriding those files in your custom theme. Custom theming is discussed more in a different piece of documentation. \r\n','Drupal Views - A Brief Overview of the GUI','','publish','open','open','','drupal-views-a-brief-overview-of-the-gui','','','2014-08-14 18:17:52','2014-08-14 18:17:52','',0,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=87',0,'post','',0),(88,1,'2014-08-14 18:12:45','2014-08-14 18:12:45','','4','','inherit','open','open','','4-2','','','2014-08-14 18:12:45','2014-08-14 18:12:45','',87,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/41.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(89,1,'2014-08-14 18:13:38','2014-08-14 18:13:38','','5','','inherit','open','open','','5-3','','','2014-08-14 18:13:38','2014-08-14 18:13:38','',87,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/52.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(90,1,'2014-08-14 18:14:24','2014-08-14 18:14:24','','6','','inherit','open','open','','6-2','','','2014-08-14 18:14:24','2014-08-14 18:14:24','',87,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/61.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(91,1,'2014-08-14 18:15:31','2014-08-14 18:15:31','If you want to make changes to the appearance of your Drupal site that you can’t make through the GUI or by using custom CSS in a theme, you may want to make custom template files. Template files control the way every piece of content on your Drupal site displays. If you wanted to completely ignore the way Drupal is supposed to be used and overwrite everything with custom html, this is how you would do it.\n\nDrupal will recognize and use properly named custom template files in a theme or subtheme instead of the default template files. Never directly modify the default template files. Instead, create either a custom theme or a sub-theme. If you want to base your theme off of an already existent theme, you should create a sub-theme. There is a documentation page <a href = \"https://www.drupal.org/node/225125\">here</a> that gives detailed instructions on how to create a sub-theme.\n\nOnce you have a custom theme or sub-theme, you can start to override Drupal’s default template files.\n\nIn your theme (which should be located at sites/all/themes/your_subtheme_name), create a folder called “templates”. It’s important that you follow this naming convention in order for Drupal to recognize your template files.\n\nDrupal template files all end with the extension .tpl.php and typically contain a mixture of html and php.\n\nThe naming schemes for different types of template overrides are given <a href =\"https://www.drupal.org/node/1089656\">here</a>. You can use template overrides for different content types, or even specific nodes. In order for your override to be seen, it is key that you use the correct naming scheme and that you have created content of the correct type.\n\nTo start out, it’s a good idea to copy the default template files into your theme. Drupal’s default page.tpl.php and html.tpl.php files can be found in modules/system. You can similarly find the default block.tpl.php in modules/block. Once you’ve copied these files into your theme, any changes you make to them will override the default files.\n\nThe default page template, page.tpl.php, by default affects all of the pages on your site. It controls things such as menus, navigation, and what content is displayed. For example, if you delete everything in the copy of page.tpl.php in your theme and replace it with “Hello World”, that’s what will show up on every page of your site (This is probably not what you want).\n\nThe default block template, block.tpl.php, affects the way that blocks look on your site. Blocks are output by Drupal modules. Examples of different blocks include the default search bar and the user login. You can see a complete list of default blocks in structure→blocks when you log into your site. You can also assign blocks to different regions of your page. Regions are how Drupal knows where to put different blocks. Regions are defined in your theme’s .info file.\n\nNode template files can be used to theme different content types. New content types can be created in the administration interface. There are a number of other possible overrides, which are given in the Drupal documentation page on custom theme hooks.\n\nIn a custom template file with the correct naming scheme, you can use a mixture of custom php and html to precisely control the way parts of your site are displayed. One thing that may be useful is to be able to print blocks in a template file.\n\nTo print blocks in a custom .tpl.php template such as page.tpl.php: \n\nPrinting only content of a block: \n<pre>\n<?php $block = module_invoke(module, hook, delta);\nprint render ($block[‘content’]); ?>\n</pre><br>\n\nPrint the entire block:\n<pre>\n<?php $block = block_load(module, delta);\n$blocktorender = _block_get_renderable_array(_block_render_blocks(array($block));\nprint drupal_render($blocktorender); ?>\n</pre><br>\n\n\nFor both of these code snippets, module is the name of the module producing the block, hook is the hook that needs to be invoked in the module, and delta is what identifies the block. The hook can be found by determining the block’s machine name, which can usually be found in whatever module you used to create the block. The delta can be found by going to structure → blocks in the administration interface and hovering over the “configure” link for the block. The url should appear in the bottom left hand corner of your screen. The part of the url right before /configure will be the block’s delta. For example, in the url \nhttp://localhost:8888/public_html/user/1#overlay=admin/structure/block/manage/views/similar_tips-block/configure\nsimilar_tips-block would be the block’s delta.\n\n','Custom Page Templates in Drupal','','inherit','open','open','','80-autosave-v1','','','2014-08-14 18:15:31','2014-08-14 18:15:31','',80,'http://blog.csteachingtips.org/?p=91',0,'revision','',0),(93,1,'2014-08-14 18:17:03','2014-08-14 18:17:03','If you want to make changes to the appearance of your Drupal site that you can’t make through the GUI or by using custom CSS in a theme, you may want to make custom template files. Template files control the way every piece of content on your Drupal site displays. If you wanted to completely ignore the way Drupal is supposed to be used and overwrite everything with custom html, this is how you would do it.\r\n\r\nDrupal will recognize and use properly named custom template files in a theme or subtheme instead of the default template files. Never directly modify the default template files. Instead, create either a custom theme or a sub-theme. If you want to base your theme off of an already existent theme, you should create a sub-theme. There is a documentation page <a href = \"https://www.drupal.org/node/225125\">here</a> that gives detailed instructions on how to create a sub-theme.\r\n\r\nOnce you have a custom theme or sub-theme, you can start to override Drupal’s default template files.\r\n\r\nIn your theme (which should be located at sites/all/themes/your_subtheme_name), create a folder called “templates”. It’s important that you follow this naming convention in order for Dru